<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="413" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,258,391]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,258,283]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Description</emphasis>
(female only): Body length 
<quantity box="[634,706,259,282]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
, wing 
<quantity box="[791,865,259,283]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
. Palpus yellow. Clypeus yellow and shiny. First flagellomere brown. Fronto-orbital plates brown, shiny. Row of katepisternal setae brownish. Mid femur entirely yellow. Hind femur narrowly white basally. Fore tarsus dark brown with gold/whitish pubescence ventrally at base of tarsomere one. Oviscape yellow and shiny, darkened preapically.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1436,1749,1772]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285302/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" startId="11.[151,264,1749,1772]" targetBox="[321,1266,443,1728]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1749,1772]" box="[151,1436,1749,1772]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,597,1749,1772]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
FIGURES 9–11. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[332,591,1750,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angularis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[332,591,1750,1772]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Cardiacephala angularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
9, female, lateral view; 10, female, dorsal view; 11, female genitalia, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1811,2016]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Head: Palpus broadened basally and gradually tapering to apex. Clypeus short, length less than half of width. First flagellomere with golden microsetulae. Frontal vitta with a narrowed depression centrally, reaching ocellar triangle. Two frontal setae. Paracephalon swollen (extending beyond the vertex), conical and shiny. Vertex flattened. Inner vertical setae insertions flat, without tubercles. Black supracervical setae sparse, weak.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1811,2016]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,151,647]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="413" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Thorax: Mesonotum golden pruinose with sparse and pale setulae. Scutellum upturned, triangular. Femora shiny and covered with sparse black microsetulae. Mid and hind tibia flattened, but sulcus on outer face weak. Wing with stigmatal and discal bands, apex clear with a dark and narrow preapical pigmentation. Crossvein r-m with small dark spot. R4+5 and M1+2 ending separately in the wing margin. A1+CuA2 as long as CuA2. Female cervical sclerite smooth, without swelling.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,647]" pageId="12" pageNumber="413">
Abdomen: Tergites covered by brownish setulae. Single spermathecal duct apically broad, ending in a cylindrical spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[438,523,298,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–11" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1749,1772]" captionTargetBox="[321,1266,443,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[321,1266,443,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 9–11. Cardiacephala angularis. 9, female, lateral view; 10, female, dorsal view; 11, female genitalia, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285302/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="413">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Paired spermathecal duct uniformly thick, apically broad before splitting into stems. Paired spermathecal duct stems thin and smooth in basal third, followed by a rounded swelling and a striate duct that leads to spermathecae. Paired spermathecae cylindrical and striate, slightly tapered basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
